To use HTTPS with Nginx and Gunicorn, you will need to follow these steps:

1. Obtain an SSL certificate: You can either use a free certificate from Let’s Encrypt or buy an SSL certificate from a trusted certificate authority.

2. Configure Nginx for HTTPS: Once you have obtained the SSL certificate, you need to configure Nginx to use it. You can create a new server block in the Nginx configuration file and set up SSL. Here is an example configuration:

```
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name example.com;

    ssl_certificate /path/to/certificate.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /path/to/privatekey.key;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    }
}
```

3. Configure Gunicorn to use SSL: Gunicorn can be configured to use SSL as well. You need to pass the SSL certificate and key to Gunicorn with the `--certfile` and `--keyfile` options. Here is an example command:

```
gunicorn myapp:app --bind 127.0.0.1:8000 --certfile /path/to/certificate.crt --keyfile /path/to/privatekey.key
```

4. Test your setup: Once you have completed the configuration steps, you can test your setup by accessing your website with HTTPS. You should see a green padlock in the browser address bar indicating that your website is secure.

That's it! You have successfully set up HTTPS with Nginx and Gunicorn.

To serve static files and templates of your Django application using Nginx when you're using Gunicorn, follow these steps:

1. First, make sure to run the `collectstatic` command in your Django application to collect all the static files in the `STATIC_ROOT` directory:

```bash
python manage.py collectstatic
```

2. Open your Nginx configuration file, which is typically located in `/etc/nginx/sites-available/` or `/etc/nginx/conf.d/`. Create or modify the configuration file for your Django application, for example, `my_django_app`.

3. Inside the `server` block, add the following location blocks to serve the static files and media files:

```nginx
server {
    # ... Your other configurations ...

    location /static/ {
        alias /path/to/your/static/folder/;
    }

    location /media/ {
        alias /path/to/your/media/folder/;
    }

    # ... Your other configurations ...
}
```

Replace `/path/to/your/static/folder/` with the actual path to your `STATIC_ROOT` directory and `/path/to/your/media/folder/` with the actual path to your `MEDIA_ROOT` directory.

4. To serve your Django application with Gunicorn, add the following location block inside the `server` block:

```nginx
server {
    # ... Your other configurations ...

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }

    # ... Your other configurations ...
}
```

Here, we assume that you're running Gunicorn on `127.0.0.1` (localhost) at port `8000`. Change the `proxy_pass` value accordingly if you're using a different setup.

5. Save the configuration file and check for any syntax errors using the following command:

```bash
sudo nginx -t
```

6. If everything is ok, restart Nginx to apply the changes:

```bash
sudo service nginx restart
```

That's it! Now Nginx will serve your Django static files and media files directly, and it will proxy other requests to your Gunicorn server.

Yes, you should configure the static and template paths in the Nginx configuration as well. The reason for that is Django web server doesn't serve static files and media files in the production environment. Nginx is configured to handle static files and reverse proxy to the Gunicorn application server.

Here's a basic configuration snippet for Nginx:

```
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name your_domain_name.com;

    location /static/ {
        alias /path/to/your/static/files/;
    }

    location /media/ {
        alias /path/to/your/media/files/;
    }

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}
```

Here, replace `your_domain_name.com` with your server's domain name or IP address, and `/path/to/your/static/files` and `/path/to/your/media/files` with the appropriate paths on your server. This configuration assumes Gunicorn is running on port 8000.

This Nginx configuration sets up a reverse proxy for your Gunicorn application server and serves your static and media files directly through Nginx.

Here is a summary of the design of the entire score calculation engine:

1. Architecture Design

The engine adopts the architecture of Flink and Kafka, mainly consisting of the following three components:

- User Behavior Recording System: used to record user behavior and send it to Kafka;
- Kafka: used to transfer data to Flink;
- Flink: used for real-time calculation of scores and to update the score account with the results.

2. Data flow Design
The data flow for score calculation is as follows:

- The user behavior recording system generates event data;
- Write the data to Kafka in a specific format;
- Kafka transfers the data to Flink;
- Flink performs the necessary calculations on the data received from Kafka;
- The calculated result is broadcasted back to the score account while awaiting a success message;
- Once the update is successful, the result is returned to Kafka.

This process is designed to perform real-time and rapid data transmission and calculation throughout the system in order to achieve the real-time calculation and updating of client scores.

3. Design of Score Calculation Rules

The score calculation rules are an important part of this engine. The engine uses the Drools rules engine, which allows for dynamic configuration and flexible management. By using a pluggable rule engine, administrators can dynamically add, modify or delete computation rules without affecting the normal operation of the system. Using a configuration center, managers can add, modify, or delete rules, and the engine can perform hot updates automatically without requiring a restart or downtime.

4. Score Calculation Function Design

When using Drools in Flink, computation rules can be encapsulated into a processing function, and the Drools rule engine can be embedded in this function. The engine uses a pluggable ProcessFunction as the processing function, which can perform real-time processing on streaming data. During the process, we pass each event data we read from the Kafka stream to the Drools rule engine for calculation, and then update the corresponding score account.

In summary, this engine uses the Drools rules engine component and combines Flink and Kafka to implement a flexible, efficient and scalable score calculation engine. It has the characteristics of real-time, fast, reliable and dynamic adjustment, and can meet the needs of enterprises in terms of large data volume and complex business logic.

